​​🇫🇷 Einbruch und Vergewaltigungsversuch auf identitäre Aktivistin

Thais, eine 22jährige französische Aktivistin, die mit mir unlängst über Eric Zemmour sprach wurde gestern von einem Araber überfallen. 

🟥 Als sie am Abend vom Training nach Hause kam schlich der tunesische "Bereicherer" hinter ihr in das Wohnhaus. Thais hörte ihn nicht weil sie Kopfhörer aufhatte. Er schaffte es hinter ihr ihre die Wohnung einzudringen. "Es ging alles extrem schnell", wie Thais sagte. Er schloss die Tür hinter ihnen und nahm den Schlüssel. Als sie im sagte er solle sofort verschwinden, begann er ihr Komplimente zu machen. 

🟥 Thais war in Panik. Sie bat ihn wieder und wieder ihre Wohnung zu verlassen, doch er machte ihr weiter Komplimente und erzählte ihr aus seinem Leben. Thais war vor Angst wie gelähmt und suchte nach einem Ausweg. Schließlich nutzte sie eine Chance griff nach dem Schlüssel den er am Tisch gelegt hatte uns versuchte die Tür zu öffnen. Der Araber befahl ihr zu warten. Als sie verneinte, griff er nach ihr, versuchte sie zu umarmen, zu küssen, hielt sie an ihren Handgelenken fest und versuchte sie zu vergewaltigen.  

🟥 Nur mit maximalem Körpereinsatz schaffte sie es sich zu befreien und die Türe zu öffnen. Alarmiert durch ihr lautes Schreien floh der arabische Vergewaltiger und sie konnte die Tür hinter sich schließen. Nach 2 Stunden schaffte sie es die Kraft zu finden, die Polizei zu rufen. Thais schrieb auf Telegramkanal:

"Wir haben Recht und was ich gestern Morgen durchgemacht habe, hat mich wieder daran erinnert. Wir beschreiben nur eine Realität, die am eigenen LEIB erleben und die diejenigen, die uns Rassisten nennen, die in ihren Elfenbeintürmen sitzen, niemals spüren müssen. 

Die Unsicherheit ist nicht nur ein Gefühl, sie dringt  in unser Zuhause ein. Wir können der Realität nicht mehr entfliehen, es liegt vor unserer Tür."

TEILEN!⚡️

🇫🇷 Attempted rape: Arab infiltrates the apartment of an identitarian activist.

Thais, a 22 year old French activist who spoke to me recently about Eric Zemmour (https://odysee.com/@MartinSellner:d/thais1:6) was attacked by an Arab yesterday. 

🟥 When she came home from training in the evening, the Tunisian "enricher" sneaked behind her into the apartment building. Thais didn't hear him because she had headphones on. He managed to enter her apartment behind her. "It all happened extremely fast," Thais said. He closed the door behind them and took the key. When she told im to leave immediately, he started complimenting her. 

🟥 Thais was in a panic. She asked him again and again to leave her apartment, but he kept complimenting her and telling her about his life. Thais was paralyzed with fear and was looking for a way out. Finally she took a chance and grabbed the key he had put on the table and tried to open the door. The Arab ordered her to wait. When she denied, he reached for her, tried to hug her, kiss her, held her by her wrists and tried to rape her.  

🟥 Only with maximum physical effort she managed to free herself and open the door. Alarmed by her loud screaming, the Arab rapist fled and she was able to close the door behind her. After 2 hours she managed to find the strength to call the police. Thais wrote on Telegram channel (https://t.me/thaisdescufon/318):

"We are right and what I went through yesterday morning reminded me again. We are only describing a reality that is experienced in our own BODY and that those who call us racists, sitting in their ivory towers, never have to feel. 

Insecurity is not just a feeling, it invades our home. We can no longer escape reality, it is at our doorstep."

I listened to him in Menomonie, WI. I do not like or trust him.

Here's the email I sent him:

Hi Eric,


I heard you speak at the Pints & Politics event held in Menomonie last Thursday evening, and also listened to your interview with Justin on the Badger State Resistance Podcast. I loved most of what you said on Thursday evening, but I do have a few questions for you.


On Thursday evening, January 6 protesters were brought up. Your statement was something to the effect of If they struck or hurt a Law Enforcement Officer, they are exactly where they should be. I agree with you, but I have some questions about this, keeping in mind that this event took place more than 11 months ago:

How many protesters are still being held in relation to this event?

Where are they being held?

In what conditions are they being held?

What charges have been brought against them?

What is being done to protect their Civil Liberties and their Constitutional Rights, specifically their 1st Amendment right to petition the Government for a redress of grievances?


On the Badger State Resistance Podcast, you stated in effect that there was fraud in the 2020 election. In my opinion, your statement that we can't "Unring that Bell" because the Law doesn't allow for it, and that fraud happens in every election and we'll never be rid of all the fraud. I want to understand you more completely here. 

How much fraud is too much fraud? Is there a certain percentage of fraud that as AG you would be ok with? Is there a threshold that in your opinion "crosses the line"?

You admit that the WEC instructed the County Clerks in all 72 Wisconsin Counties to break the law, and yet, because only one sheriff's office investigated one nursing home, you are not willing to act. Why? Your own County Clerk was instructed to break the law. I'd like to hear your reasoning on this.

When you say that the law doesn't allow for punishment of a clear crime and a redress of election fraud, does that mean that you are not willing to do the hard work that would be required to pioneer election reform that both addresses this past crime(s) and ensures that it never happens again?

There are a lot of concerned citizens right now looking for our Elected Officials to stand up and do the right thing. In the case that they will not, we are also vetting our new candidates more closely than we have ever done before. As an acting District Attorney, I believe that there are steps that can be taken, and will be watching for those.


I look forward to hearing your thoughts on these matters.


Sincerely,


Carol M. Breslin
